## What I Learned
Today I solved a reflected XSS lab where user input was reflected inside a JavaScript string instead of normal HTML.

The input appeared inside a `<script>` block in a pattern similar to:

```javascript
var searchTerms = 'USERINPUT';
This confirmed that the single quote was not safely escaped.
Working Payload
Plain text
';alert(1)//
Why It Worked
The payload worked by:
Closing the original JavaScript string with '
Executing alert(1)
Using // to comment out the trailing quote and prevent syntax errors
Key Takeaway
In XSS testing, context decides the payload.
Before using any payload, I now know to first check:
Is the input reflected in HTML?
Is it inside an attribute?
Is it inside JavaScript?
Are special characters being encoded or escaped?
